<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1232,1979]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">
A male specimen was designated as the 
<typeStatus box="[641,739,1377,1403]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">holotype</typeStatus>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Murayama, S." box="[779,983,1376,1403]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" pagination="32 - 35" refId="ref6107" refString="Murayama, S. (1995) Descriptions of 3 new species and 5 new races of Chinese butterflies from Yunnan Province. Nature &amp; Insects, 30 (14), 32 - 35 [in Japanese]" type="journal article" year="1995">Murayama (1995)</bibRefCitation>
, and the specimen was retrieved in 
<collectionCode box="[1376,1437,1377,1403]" country="Japan" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/pcbg-hhf5" name="Lake Biwa Museum" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">LBM</collectionCode>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,296,1412,1439]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–36" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1902,1927]" captionTargetBox="[172,1425,181,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[163,1425,181,1877]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 19–36. 19–21. Apostictopterus fulginosus jiangxiensis Murayama, 1983, holotype; 22–24. Aeromachus inachus jiujiangana Murayama, 1983, holotype; 25–27. Pedesta masuriensis cuneomaculata Murayama, 1995, holotype; 28–30. Thoressa dianchiana Murayama, 1995, holotype; 31–33. Thoressa nanshaona Murayama, 1995, holotype; 34–36. Lobocla bifasciata disparalis Murayama, 1995, holotype. Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990961" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990961/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Figs. 25–27</figureCitation>
; Dried Insect Database Reg. no. 1500022032).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1232,1979]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">
<bibRefCitation author="Huang, H." box="[199,356,1449,1475]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" pagination="193 - 200" refId="ref5475" refString="Huang, H. (2011) Notes on the genus Thoressa Swinhoe, [1913] from China, with the description of a new species. Atalanta, 42, 193 - 200." type="journal article" year="2011">Huang (2011)</bibRefCitation>
treated 
<emphasis box="[450,621,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">cuneomaculata</emphasis>
as a junior subjective synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Swinhoe, 1912)" baseAuthorityName="Swinhoe" baseAuthorityYear="1912" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="masuriensis" subSpecies="tali">
<emphasis box="[1023,1313,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Thoressa masuriensis tali</emphasis>
(Swinhoe, 1912)
</taxonomicName>
. We agree that 
<emphasis box="[393,564,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">cuneomaculata</emphasis>
is a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[759,796,1485,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tali">
<emphasis box="[759,796,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">tali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The nominate subspecies 
<taxonomicName authority="Moore, 1878" authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[1101,1388,1485,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="masuriensis">
<emphasis box="[1101,1235,1486,1511]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">masuriensis</emphasis>
Moore, 1878
</taxonomicName>
and subspecies 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[280,317,1521,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tali">
<emphasis box="[280,317,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">tali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are significantly different in appearance (
<figureCitation box="[795,934,1521,1548]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Figs. 46–49</figureCitation>
), but 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, W. H." box="[999,1151,1521,1547]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" refId="ref5130" refString="Evans, W. H. (1949) A Catalogue of the Hesperiidae from Europe, Asia and Australia in the British Museum (Natural History). BMNH, London, 502 pp., 53 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 105941" type="book" year="1949">Evans (1949)</bibRefCitation>
considered them as conspecific. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[368,502,1558,1583]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="masuriensis">
<emphasis box="[368,502,1558,1583]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">masuriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[517,694,1556,1583]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Figs. 46–47, 50</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[757,794,1557,1583]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tali">
<emphasis box="[757,794,1557,1583]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">tali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[810,986,1556,1583]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Figs. 48–49, 51</figureCitation>
) are two different species, supported by distinctions in genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[434,571,1592,1619]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Figs. 50–51</figureCitation>
) and the genetic divergence of 
<collectionCode box="[934,982,1593,1619]" country="Portugal" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:14498" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:14498" name="University of Coimbra Botany Department" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" type="Herbarium">COI</collectionCode>
barcode between them (12–13%, 
<tableCitation captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,239,154,178]" captionText="TABLE 1. The p-distance on COI sequence between exemplars of Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan) used in the present study." pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Table 1</tableCitation>
). They may be separated by the following features: 1) uncus bent with blunt tips in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[1117,1251,1630,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="masuriensis">
<emphasis box="[1117,1251,1630,1655]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">masuriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1266,1349,1628,1655]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
) versus straight with narrowed tips in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[503,540,1665,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tali">
<emphasis box="[503,540,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">tali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[558,644,1664,1691]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
); 2) left harpe with inner one of terminal processes as small lobe in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[151,285,1702,1727]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="masuriensis">
<emphasis box="[151,285,1702,1727]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">masuriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[301,382,1700,1727]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
) versus produced serrate teeth in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[762,799,1701,1727]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tali">
<emphasis box="[762,799,1701,1727]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">tali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[815,899,1700,1727]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
); 3) phallus short and stout in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[1241,1375,1702,1727]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="masuriensis">
<emphasis box="[1241,1375,1702,1727]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">masuriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
) versus elongate and slender in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[540,577,1737,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tali">
<emphasis box="[540,577,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">tali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[593,676,1736,1763]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–51" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1967]" captionTargetBox="[173,1419,439,1914]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,417,1917]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 46–51. Pedesta masuriensis (Nepal) and P. tali (Yunnan). 46, upperside of male P. masuriensis, 47, underside of male P. masuriensis, 48, upperside of male P. tali, 49, upperside of male P. tali, 50, male genitalia of of P. masuriensis (genitalia preparation JYL 691), 51, male genitalia of P. tali (genitalia preparation JYL 692). Scale bar = 1 cm (46–49); 1 mm (50–51)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3990965" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3990965/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
). Those 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[772,906,1738,1763]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="masuriensis">
<emphasis box="[772,906,1738,1763]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">masuriensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
molecular samples in 
<collectingCountry box="[1158,1225,1737,1763]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">China</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Li, Y. Y. &amp; Zhu, J. Q. &amp; Ge, C. &amp; Wang, Y. &amp; Zhao, Z. M. &amp; Ma, S. J. &amp; Hoffmann, A. A. &amp; Endersby, N. M. &amp; Liu, Q. X. &amp; Yu, W. D. &amp; Jiang, W. B." box="[1239,1394,1737,1763]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" pagination="294" refId="ref5780" refString="Li, Y. Y., Zhu, J. Q., Ge, C., Wang, Y., Zhao, Z. M., Ma, S. J., Hoffmann, A. A., Endersby, N. M., Liu, Q. X., Yu, W. D. &amp; Jiang, W. B. (2019) Molecular phylogeny and historical biogeography of the butterfly tribe Aeromachini Tutt (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae) from China. Cells, 8, 294. https: // doi. org / 10.3390 / cells 8040294" type="journal article" year="2019">
Li 
<emphasis box="[1273,1329,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
) all belong to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[263,300,1773,1799]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tali">
<emphasis box="[263,300,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">tali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1232,1979]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">
<bibRefCitation author="Huang, H." box="[199,357,1809,1835]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" pagination="193 - 200" refId="ref5475" refString="Huang, H. (2011) Notes on the genus Thoressa Swinhoe, [1913] from China, with the description of a new species. Atalanta, 42, 193 - 200." type="journal article" year="2011">Huang (2011)</bibRefCitation>
was correct in merging the Chinese taxa of 
<taxonomicName authority="Swinhoe, 1913" authorityName="Swinhoe" authorityYear="1913" box="[876,1159,1809,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[876,978,1809,1835]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Thoressa</emphasis>
Swinhoe, 1913
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hemming, 1934" authorityName="Hemming" authorityYear="1934" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1219,1308,1809,1835]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Pedesta</emphasis>
Hemming, 1934
</taxonomicName>
. His taxonomic treatment, however, was not complete because he did not include the 
<typeStatus box="[1157,1205,1845,1871]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swinhoe" authorityYear="1913" box="[1328,1430,1845,1871]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1328,1430,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Thoressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="sensu Evans (1949)" authorityName="sensu Evans" authorityYear="1949" box="[274,601,1881,1907]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[274,444,1881,1907]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Thoressa sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, W. H." box="[451,601,1881,1907]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" refId="ref5130" refString="Evans, W. H. (1949) A Catalogue of the Hesperiidae from Europe, Asia and Australia in the British Museum (Natural History). BMNH, London, 502 pp., 53 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 105941" type="book" year="1949">Evans (1949)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
was polyphyletic and is now divided into three genera based on molecular evidences (
<bibRefCitation author="Huang, Z. F. &amp; Chiba, H. &amp; Jin, J. &amp; Kizhakke, A. G. &amp; Wang, M. &amp; Kunte, K. &amp; Fan, X. L." box="[277,486,1917,1943]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" pagination="163 - 178" refId="ref5551" refString="Huang, Z. F., Chiba, H., Jin, J., Kizhakke, A. G., Wang, M., Kunte, K. &amp; Fan, X. L. (2019) A multilocus phylogenetic framework of the tribe Aeromachini (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae: Hesperiinae), with implication for taxonomy and biogeography. Systematic Entomology, 44, 163 - 178. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / syen. 12322" type="journal article" year="2019">
Huang 
<emphasis box="[361,418,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
). Those species assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Evans" authorityYear="1949" box="[803,905,1917,1943]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Thoressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[803,905,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Thoressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Huang, H." box="[948,1104,1917,1943]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" pagination="193 - 200" refId="ref5475" refString="Huang, H. (2011) Notes on the genus Thoressa Swinhoe, [1913] from China, with the description of a new species. Atalanta, 42, 193 - 200." type="journal article" year="2011">Huang (2011)</bibRefCitation>
indeed should be included in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hemming" authorityYear="1934" box="[151,240,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,240,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Pedesta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Chiba &amp; Tsukiyama &amp; Liang &amp; Wang &amp; Shen &amp; Hsu" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[378,510,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pedesta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tali" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[378,510,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">Pedesta tali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[518,646,1953,1979]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[518,646,1953,1979]" pageId="3" pageNumber="283" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is the valid name for this taxon.
</paragraph>
